04171nam a22005175i 9780822385110DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20042003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223851107 a10.1515/97808223851102doi  a(DE-B1597)552522  a(OCoLC)1058486182  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aML3411.5 -- L38 2003 7aPER0030002bisacsh04a306.4/841 aLawrence, Tim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLove Saves the Day :bA History of American Dance Music Culture, 1970-1979 /cTim Lawrence. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource (528 p.) :b73 photos and Illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. beginnings. House Parties and Discotheques -- t2. consolidation. Party Pariahs and the Path to Permanent Revolution -- t3. pollination. The Rise of the Downtown Party Network -- t4. recognition. The Crystallization of a Sound -- t5. visibility. The Message of Love and the Disco Mix -- t6. expansion. Record Pools, Music Labels, New Clubs -- t7. prominence. Forums, Formats, Franchises -- t8. ascendancy. Eurodisco, Midtown, Downtown, Out-of-Town -- t9. dominance. Disco Takes Over -- t10. turbulence. Backlash and Survival -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tSelected Discography -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOpening with David Mancuso's seminal "Love Saves the Day" Valentine's party, Tim Lawrence tells the definitive story of American dance music culture in the 1970s-from its subterranean roots in NoHo and Hell's Kitchen to its gaudy blossoming in midtown Manhattan to its wildfire transmission through America's suburbs and urban hotspots such as Chicago, Boston, San Francisco, Los Angeles, Newark, and Miami.Tales of nocturnal journeys, radical music making, and polymorphous sexuality flow through the arteries of Love Saves the Day like hot liquid vinyl. They are interspersed with a detailed examination of the era's most powerful djs, the venues in which they played, and the records they loved to spin-as well as the labels, musicians, vocalists, producers, remixers, party promoters, journalists, and dance crowds that fueled dance music's tireless engine.Love Saves the Day includes material from over three hundred original interviews with the scene's most influential players, including David Mancuso, Nicky Siano, Tom Moulton, Loleatta Holloway, Giorgio Moroder, Francis Grasso, Frankie Knuckles, and Earl Young. It incorporates more than twenty special dj discographies-listing the favorite records of the most important spinners of the disco decade-and a more general discography cataloging some six hundred releases. Love Saves the Day also contains a unique collection of more than seventy rare photos.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Dance / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822385110zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822385110423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822385110.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles